 antibodies","Produces antibodies with lower affinity","Produces predominantly IgG antibodies","Generates lower antibody titres"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe secondary humoral immune response differs from the primary response in several key ways. \u003Cstrong\u003EPredominantly IgG antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E are produced during the secondary response, whereas IgM dominates the primary response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe secondary response is much faster than the primary response, typically peaking within 1-3 days rather than \u003Cstrong\u003Epeaks after 7-10 days\u003C/strong\u003E. While IgM dominates the primary response, the secondary response \u003Cstrong\u003Eproduces predominantly IgG antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E rather than IgM. The secondary response \u003Cstrong\u003Eproduces antibodies with higher affinity\u003C/strong\u003E due to affinity maturation, not lower affinity, and \u003Cstrong\u003Egenerates much higher antibody titres\u003C/strong\u003E compared to the primary response. The rapid and enhanced response occurs because memory B cells generated during the primary response quickly recognise and respond to the antigen, producing high-affinity IgG antibodies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The secondary humoral immune response produces antibodies within 1-3 days of antigen exposure, compared to 7-10 days for the primary response.","IgG is the predominant antibody class in the secondary immune response, while IgM dominates the primary response.","The secondary response generates higher antibody titres and increased antibody affinity due to memory B cells."],"references":["Bona, C. A., \u0026 Bonilla, F. A. (2019). Textbook of immunology. CRC press","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Janeway CA Jr, Travers P, Walport M, et al. Immunobiology: The Immune System in Health and Disease. 